# how limma works:
#
# step 1 - lmFit():
#   fits a linear model to each gene
#   the design matrix tells it which samples belong to which group
#   think of it as running a regression for every gene at once
#
# step 2 - eBayes():
#   applies empirical bayes shrinkage
#   borrows information across all genes to stabilize variance
#   this is what makes limma reliable with only n=5 per group
#
# step 3 - topTable():
#   ranks genes by statistical significance
#   returns: logFC (fold change), p-value, adjusted p-value (FDR)
#   adj.P.Val < 0.05 means the result is statistically significant
#   logFC > 1 means the gene doubled in expression
#   logFC < -1 means the gene halved in expression


# 4. define hypothesis genes to track

# these are the genes specifically mentioned in our hypothesis
# we will check whether these show up as significant in each comparison
hypothesis_genes <- c(
